      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While critics argue the UN is a tool of great power influence, most historians maintain its legitimacy extends beyond just enforcement to its role as an essential forum for dialogue and legitimacy-granting for states. They view the Organization not as a miracle cure for global peace, but as the necessary baseline institution that forces confrontation and mediums for negotiation even when faced with structural paralysis. Therefore, its inability to solve every crisis does not equate to a total loss of authority, as its lack of a perfect record still allows its institutions to evolve and remain the default framework for international order.",
      "source": "target",
